            <ArticleTitle>Coherent phase transfer and pulse compression at 1.4  μm in a backward-wave OPO.</ArticleTitle>
            <Pagination>
                <MedlinePgn>3066-3069</MedlinePgn>
            </Pagination>
            <ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1364/OL.44.003066</ELocationID>
            <Abstract>
                <AbstractText>The frequency modulation transfer property of a backward-wave optical parametric oscillator (BWOPO) is investigated in the context of near-IR pulse compression. The maximum transferrable bandwidth from the pump to the forward wave in a BWOPO is determined by the group dispersion mismatch. In comparison, the third-order phase introduced in a single-grating compressor setup is more detrimental to achieve optimum compression of the BWOPO forward wave. Nevertheless, we demonstrate a 220 GHz bandwidth transfer from 800 nm to 1.4 μm, with a compression factor of 115, leading to near-IR pulses as short as 1.3 ps with μJ energy.</AbstractText>
            </Abstract>
